Building Dashboards for Bank Credit Risk Analyses

A few things to do before you start working on the Dashboards.

- Start by installing the packages you need. I will set message=FALSE and warning=FALSE so they will not show up in the HTML output.

#install.packages("dplyr") #only need to run this code once to install the package
library("dplyr") #need to call the libary before you use the package
#install.packages("tidyr")
library("tidyr")
library("rpivotTable")
library("knitr")

The worksheet Base Data in the Excel file Bank Credit Risk Data provides information about 425 bank customers who had applied for loans. Each of the column is defined as follows:

  • Loan Purpose : Type of purpose for the loan applied
  • Checking : Checking account balance
  • Savings : Savings account balance
  • Months Customer: Number of months has been a customer of the bank
  • Months Employed: Number of months in employment
  • Gender: Gender
  • Marital Status: Marital status
  • Age: Age in years
  • Housing: Housing type
  • Years: Number of years at current residence
  • Job: Job type
  • Credit Risk: Credit-risk classification by the bank

- Be sure to set working directory and import the datafile.

#import excel file into RStudio
library(readxl)
Bank_Credit_Risk_Data <- read_excel("Bank Credit Risk Data.xlsx", 
                               sheet = "Base Data", skip = 2) 
View(Bank_Credit_Risk_Data)
BD<-Bank_Credit_Risk_Data

- Check that you have entered the data correctly by using the head() and summary() functions.

3) Loan Customer Analyses Dashboard

Purpose: To compare loan types across different customer profiles (e.g. gender)

# Create contingency table for loan purpose and gender with gender as columns and loan purpose as rows
BD2 <- BD %>% group_by(`Loan Purpose`,Gender) %>% tally() #same as BD2 <- BD%>%count(`Loan Purpose`,Gender)
BD2.spread<- BD2 %>% spread(key=Gender,value=n)
BD2.spread[is.na(BD2.spread)]<-0 #convert NA to 0 value
kable(BD2.spread, caption = "Contingency table for Loan Type & Gender")
Contingency table for Loan Type & Gender

Education 12 11
Furniture 37 48

New Car 34 70

Repairs 4 8
Retraining 0 2
Small Appliance 32 73

#plot the grouped barplot
barmatrix<-as.matrix(BD2.spread[,c(2,3)]) #first we need to extract and convert the 2nd&3rd columns into a matrix
bar_Col<-c("red","orange","yellow","green","blue","gray","pink","brown","cyan","violet")
barplot(barmatrix,names.arg=c("Female","Male"),col=bar_Col, beside = TRUE, ylim=c(0,100), main="Loan Purpose and Gender") 
legend("topleft", cex=0.5, fill=bar_Col, BD2.spread$`Loan Purpose`)

# Create contingency table for loan purpose and gender with loan purpose as columns and gender as rows
BD3 <- BD %>% group_by(`Loan Purpose`,Gender) %>% tally()
BD3.spread<- BD3 %>% spread(key=`Loan Purpose`,value=n)
BD3.spread[is.na(BD3.spread)]<-0 #convert NA to 0 value
kable(BD3.spread, caption = "Contingency Table for Gender & Loan Purpose")
Contingency Table for Gender & Loan Purpose

#plot the grouped barplot
barmatrix.BD3<-as.matrix(BD3.spread[,c(2:11)])
barplot(barmatrix.BD3, beside = TRUE, col =c("pink","blue"), main="Loan Purpose and Gender", ylim=c(0,80), cex.names=0.6,las=2) 
legend("topleft", cex=1, fill=c("pink","blue"), BD3.spread$Gender)

# plot horizontal grouped barplot
barplot(barmatrix.BD3, beside = TRUE, horiz=TRUE, col =c("pink","blue"), main="Loan Purpose and Gender", xlim=c(0,80), cex.names=0.8, las=1) 
legend("bottomright", cex=1, fill=c("pink","blue"), BD3.spread$Gender)

Since both variables are categorical variables, we will use the grouped bar chart to compare frequencies across of loan types across each gender type (female and male). From the charts, we can see frequency of loans are generally higher for MALES compared to FEMALES, regardless of type of loans (except for Education).

4) Customer Savings Analyses Dashboard

Purpose: To conduct pareto analyses on savings to understand what percentage of loan customers contribute to 80% of total savings amongst loan customers.

#extract only the Savings column and sort in descending order
BD.sav<-BD %>% select (Savings)%>% arrange(desc(Savings))
#compute the percentage of savings over total savings
BD.sav$Percentage<-BD.sav$Savings/sum(BD.sav$Savings)
#compute cumulative percentage for Savings
BD.sav$Cumulative<-cumsum(BD.sav$Percentage)
#compute cumulative percentage of customers from top most savings
BD.sav$Cumulative.cust<-as.numeric(rownames(BD))/nrow(BD)

which(BD.sav$Cumulative>0.8)[1]
## [1] 86
# compute percentage ofcustomers with top 80% savings
which(BD.sav$Cumulative>0.8)[1]/nrow(BD)
## [1] 0.2023529

From the Pareto Analyses, we see that about 86 (out of 425) customers of 20% of the customers contribute to 80% of the total savings in the bank.
